<p>In <a href="/wiki/Computer_science" title="Computer science">computer science</a>, <b>ACID</b> (<i>Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, Durability</i>) is a set of properties that guarantee that <a href="/wiki/Database_transactions" title="Database transactions" class="mw-redirect">database transactions</a> are processed reliably. In the context of <a href="/wiki/Database" title="Database">databases</a>, a single logical operation on the data is called a transaction. An example of a transaction is a transfer of funds from one bank account to another, even though it might consist of multiple individual operations (such as debiting one account and crediting another).</p>
<p>Although <a href="/wiki/Jim_Gray_(computer_scientist)" title="Jim Gray (computer scientist)">Jim Gray</a> is credited with defining, in the late 1970s, these key transaction properties of a reliable system, and with helping to develop the technologies that automatically achieve these,<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> the acronym ACID was coined by <a href="/w/index.php?title=Andreas_Reuter&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Andreas Reuter (page does not exist)">Andreas Reuter</a> and <a href="/w/index.php?title=Theo_Haerder&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Theo Haerder (page does not exist)">Theo Haerder</a> in 1983.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
